<br>
Shaede and her custos and elemental were ushered to the door of the manse by another one of the skeletal servitors. The bone gate crawled closed behind them with the same unsettling noise. At the door the skeleton turned back to patrolling as Shaede and her guardians entered the House.<br>
<br>
In the foyer, a wizened servant by the name of Naneth bowed deeply before Shaede. She knew the old Teir’Dal well, as he always met her there when she visited Khasirath. He wore the charcoal grey livery of the House, with the silver House sigil neatly pinned to his shirt.<br>
<br>
“Hail Matron K`Thalion. I shall take ye to see Master Khasirath, but your servants shall have to wait in the main hall.” He said, his voice quiet and well schooled.<br>
<br>
A slight frown of concern creased Shaede’s brow, but she nodded, “Very well, if that is how it must be.”<br>
<br>
Naneth bowed deeply again, “I apologize for the inconvenience, Matron. Please follow me.”<br>
<br>
The servant led Shaede and her guardians down the richly appointed halls of the manse, pausing before the great hall to show the custos and elemental where they could await their Matron. Once they were settled Naneth led Shaede deeper into the manse, through the halls and out a door into the courtyard.<br>
<br>
The buildings of House S`Therik were four in number, all contained within a single natural chamber in the underground haven of Neriak. The buildings framed the courtyard, the large area smooth-floored and bordered by a narrow and elegant rock garden.<br>
<br>
In the center of the courtyard Shaede saw the Reaper of the Harvest. He was fully armoured, and in the middle of what seemed to be a duel with a large and powerful Kobold, obviously one native to Nagafen’s Lair. The Knight and beast circled and clashed, snarling at one another as they fought.<br>
<br>
The beast wore a wide metal collar, and laid into Khasirath in a fury of claw and fang. Khasirath fought back with great skill, armed with his shield and a wooden practice sword that was curved something like a saber. In the background of the fight stood two servants, one male and one female. Each held a strange wand, and the female had a whip coiled at her hip. They watched the fight silently.<br>
<br>
Shaede recognized the female as Alartha, one of the Reaper’s personal servants who worked at times in the Grange for her master. Naneth led Shaede just into the courtyard, and motioned for her to wait. Carefully the old servant neared the battling pair.<br>
<br>
Shaede stood back and watched the fight curiously. The Reaper was a brutal fighter whom she had hunted with many times over a great many years. She noticed that as he fought the Kobold he was not using his dark magics, simply the force of sword and shield, and his agility in dodging and turning the monster’s attacks. It was quite fascinating to watch him fight the frenzied beast. Yet his pace seemed relaxed, as if he did not seek to best the creature, only to prolong the battle.<br>
<br>
It did not take long at all for Khasirath to notice Naneth’s approach. He nodded once to the servant and took two steps back from the Kobold. Before the beast could charge again, Khasirath thrust his shield hand forward, palm out. A writhing black aura surrounded his hand instantly. “Rr’kek! Halt!” he commanded.<br>
<br>
The slavering Kobold’s ears flattened at the command, and its eyes rolled in fear as it noticed the aura around the Reaper’s hand. Instantly it fell to the ground, writhing as it bared its throat, letting out a deep whimpering yowl of submission.<br>
<br>
The Reaper let the aura of the Father’s Touch fade away as he motioned to the two servants. He handed his practice sword and shield to the male, and instructed Alartha to return Rr’kek to his pen. Shaede noticed that the fierce Kobold followed the servant off to one of the low buildings at the back of the compound like a dog on a leash, its scraggly tail half-wagging submissively.<br>
<br>
As the servants went about their tasks, Khasirath walked over to Shaede, pulling off his helm and holding it under his arm. His long moon-white hair was bound tightly back at his neck, and a light sheen of sweat glistened on his forehead from the workout. <br>
<br>
Khasirath bowed his head in greeting as he stopped before Shaede.<br>
<br>
“Hate to thee, Matron. Let us go inside so that we may talk.”<br>
