<br>
-----------------<br>
<br>
Khasirath led Shaede back into the manor house and through the halls to a small library furnished with a pair of tables, each with a pair of high-backed chairs beside them. A few mage-light sconces provided dim violet light, more than enough for Teir’Dal to comfortably read by. After they entered he shut the door behind them to ensure their privacy.<br>
<br>
Shaede swept one of the tables clear and opened her dimensional bag, pulling out the maps and books she had brought with her.<br>
<br>
Khasirath raised an eyebrow at the mess she was making, but waited silently for Shaede to prepare.<br>
<br>
Shaede said, “I do not know where to begin Reaper. I stand accused of two crimes now, neither of which I can disprove immediately.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath nodded, looking Shaede over slowly, noting the unnatural grey of her hair and the intensity of her eyes.<br>
<br>
Shaede continued, returning the Reaper’s glance, “But the second...” Her eyes danced with dark hate, “I WILL prove my innocence on.”<br>
<br>
She shook with barely controlled rage, “I did not take the Prophet. I may have issues with the man but I am not a kidnapper nor am I a murderer of Teir’Dal.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath nodded, “Despite the conclusion many could draw that the disappearance is linked to the charges he would bring against you, I have not believed you would be capable of such an act. I know your deep devotion to your House, Matron. And since you yourself confessed to me and the Thresher the things that brought Nospiratus to doubt you before he was taken, his disappearance would not prevent the inquiry entirely at any rate.”<br>
<br>
Shade looked deep into Khasirath’s eyes, “My guilt or lack of guilt in the first matter is nothing worse then I have faced in the past. I would sooner kill myself then allow anything to happen to Nospiratus.... or Xareth.”<br>
<br>
“I understand, Shaede. On the first charge... I think Innoruuk Himself is the only one who can make that determination. As to the second... The Prophet must be found.”<br>
<br>
Shaede nodded, “For now...We need to find the Prophet.”<br>
<br>
Shaede pointed to the maps. “These are ancient maps of the tunnels beneath Neriak. These were drawn up at the time of their construction.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath nodded as he bent over the table to study the old maps. “Indeed... These are quite a handsome find. I imagine there may be some newer additions, but this is a good start.”<br>
<br>
She then pointed to the first tome. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   ‘The Rites of Final Destruction’ </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was penned in Elven on the cover. “These are the rites and rituals used by ancient magi to battle those of the blood.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath looked at the book with distaste, “A Tome of the Spurned, then?”<br>
<br>
She shook her head, “No, older then that. Rumor has it that it was from before the Koada`Dal were driven from Takish Hiz by Solusek Ro.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath raised an eyebrow in surprise.<br>
<br>
Shaede said, “It would seem the lightcrawlers have a use after all. Their fanatical beliefs in the false ones caused them to call a Jihad against those of the blood.”<br>
<br>
Shaede touched the cover of the book thoughtfully, “These are arcane rites, not divine ones.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath nodded slowly as he looked at the Tome. “I have never studied the magics other than Necromancy... I do not know if I would be able to make out what the book contains.”<br>
<br>
She opened the tome to a marked page. “This shows weapons and mundane items to force them into a slumber so that the rites may be performed.”  Turning to another marked page she said, “This shows how to protect oneself from their charms.”<br>
<br>
She lowered her head, disappointed, “I have not located something to break the charms on one that is already captured....”<br>
<br>
Khasirath sighed deeply in thought, “Still, this will be most useful. It will help those who have not yet fallen. And perhaps we can find other tomes. Remember, the Thresher was once so cursed, and we helped see him cleansed of the taint.”<br>
<br>
“What now though... That monster, that creature,” she spat with hate, “is going to rip us apart from the inside out? The Harvest cannot survive this sundering.”<br>
<br>
“We must survive, Shaede. And we must seek Innoruuk's guidance in this. That is what I plan to do this very eve...” his eyes grew dark as he looked away from the table, “It will not be an easy thing, you understand. But with the Mad One missing, and Pravdameer unavailable I feel that I must.”<br>
<br>
She watched the Reaper, a look of respect and admiration on her face, “You and I have not always seen eye to eye... However, I have always respected you for your control and countenance. I will stand with you and the Thresher against anything, and I will stand and guard you while you commune with the Prince.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath looked back to Shaede with a ghost of a smile on his lips. “You are very brave, Shaede. And I am pleased to see that you have come out of the first shock of the accusations willing to act. If you truly wish it, I will allow you to be present, though there is little need to guard me. My physical body will be secure enough, ‘tis my soul that will be sent before the Father, and none can protect me should He find me unworthy.”<br>
<br>
He paused, thoughtfully, “In fact, I feel it may be better for you to spend the time translating and distributing the information you have found, perhaps finding others to help in further research while I do this thing.”<br>
<br>
“I can do so while my pet and I watch over you. I will not take any risks with Mythral involved.” Her face glowed with hatred as she mentioned his name.<br>
<br>
Khasirath nodded, “As you wish. It will be done this eve, here in House S`Therik where I can be sure of my safety. My sister, the Prophetess, shall be assisting me in the actual offering and communion.”<br>
<br>
She nodded sharply, &quot;You are a far braver man then I. I remember all too well the pain that the Father offers...”<br>
<br>
Khasirath nods again, determination and haunting memory of that pain mingled deeply in his eyes. &quot;For the Harvest, I will face whatever I must.”<br>
<br>
The Reaper looked over the maps and tomes again. “I am sorry, Shaede. But I have much to prepare… If ye wish to remain, I will have a servant assigned to getting you what you need. There is a guest suite where you can take your things, and I will have your custos and elemental brought to you there.”<br>
<br>
Shaede nodded slowly, “That will be fine, thank you.”<br>
<br>
